---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<Base
  title="Glossary"
  description="A guide to the philosophical and taxonomic terms used in Barking"
>
<style>
  .glossary-container {
    max-width: 780px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 5rem 2rem 5rem;
  }

  .glossary-header {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  h1 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
    font-size: 3rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    line-height: 1.1;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 2;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
    max-width: 560px;
  }

  .glossary-intro {
    font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 2.1;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    max-width: 640px;
  }

  .glossary-section {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  .glossary-section-title {
    font-family: 'Karla', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 1.8rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.8rem;
  }
  .glossary-section-title::after {
    content: '';
    flex: 1;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--rule);
  }

  .glossary-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.8rem;
  }

  .glossary-term {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .glossary-term:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .term-word {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .term-def {
    font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    line-height: 2;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    margin-top: 4rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }
  .back-link:hover { color: var(--ink); }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .glossary-container {
      padding: 3rem 1.5rem;
    }
    .glossary-term {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.5rem;
    }
    .term-word {
      margin-bottom: 0.2rem;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 2.2rem;
    }
  }
</style>

<div class="glossary-container">
  <div class="glossary-header">
    <h1>Glossary</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">
      A guide to the philosophical and taxonomic terms used throughout this collection
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="glossary-intro">
    The poems in <em>Barking</em> are organized through four taxonomic lenses: <strong>Domain</strong> (subject matter), <strong>Atmosphere</strong> (tonal quality), <strong>Ground</strong> (philosophical approach), and <strong>Crux</strong> (conceptual pivot). Many of these terms draw from philosophy, phenomenology, and contemplative traditions. This glossary explains the more specialized ones.
  </div>

  <!-- Ground terms -->
  <section class="glossary-section">
    <h2 class="glossary-section-title">Ground (Philosophical Approach)</h2>
    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Nondual</div>
        <div class="term-def">Investigating experience without presuming inherent separation between subject and object, self and other, inside and outside. The poem doesn't affirm or deny duality but examines what happens when that distinction is questioned.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Apophatic</div>
        <div class="term-def">Approaching truth through negation—saying what something <em>isn't</em> rather than what it is. Common in mystical and contemplative traditions where direct description fails or obscures.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Phenomenological</div>
        <div class="term-def">Attending to the structure of lived experience as it appears, bracketing assumptions about underlying reality. The poem works at the level of how things show up, not what they "really are."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Ontological</div>
        <div class="term-def">Concerned with the nature of being, existence, and what it means for something to <em>be</em>. Questions about what exists, how things exist, or whether existence itself has a structure.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Epistemological</div>
        <div class="term-def">Investigating the nature and limits of knowledge—how we know what we claim to know, what counts as knowing, and where knowledge breaks down.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Existential</div>
        <div class="term-def">Engaging with questions of meaning, freedom, choice, and the human condition. Often characterized by confronting the givens of existence—death, isolation, contingency.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Deconstructive</div>
        <div class="term-def">Exposing internal contradictions and instabilities in concepts, revealing how meaning undoes itself. Not destruction but close reading that shows a term's dependence on what it excludes.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Idealist</div>
        <div class="term-def">Treating mind, consciousness, or ideas as fundamental rather than derivative. Reality is understood through or as mental/experiential rather than material/external.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Axiomatic</div>
        <div class="term-def">Proceeding from first principles taken as self-evident. The poem builds from foundational statements rather than arguing toward them.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Crux terms -->
  <section class="glossary-section">
    <h2 class="glossary-section-title">Crux (Conceptual Pivot)</h2>
    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Groundlessness</div>
        <div class="term-def">The recognition that experience has no ultimate foundation or fixed point of reference. Every ground turns out to rest on something else, indefinitely.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Inseparability</div>
        <div class="term-def">The impossibility of cleanly dividing apparently distinct phenomena or aspects of experience. Not fusion but the failure of the cut to find purchase.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Reflexivity</div>
        <div class="term-def">The self-referential loop where awareness becomes aware of itself, or a concept applies to itself. The tool examining the tool; the eye trying to see itself seeing.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Ineffability</div>
        <div class="term-def">That which resists or exceeds linguistic capture—the unsayable. Not merely difficult to express but structurally beyond expression, yet somehow indicated.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Aporetic</div>
        <div class="term-def">Marked by unresolvable paradox or impasse—from Greek <em>aporia</em>, "without passage." The poem arrives at a point where contradictory conclusions both hold.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Tautological</div>
        <div class="term-def">Circular reasoning where a statement refers back to itself. Often revealing something is true by definition rather than discovered—"it is what it is" as endpoint.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Inversion</div>
        <div class="term-def">A reversal where foreground becomes background, subject becomes object, or the usual hierarchy flips. What was assumed foundational turns out to depend on what it was supposed to ground.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Paradox</div>
        <div class="term-def">A statement or situation that contradicts itself yet may point to truth. Not error but productive tension where logic buckles under pressure.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Dissolution</div>
        <div class="term-def">The breaking down or dissipation of a form, boundary, or structure. Not into chaos but into what was there before the form congealed.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Unrepresentable</div>
        <div class="term-def">That which cannot be captured in image, concept, or language without remainder. Not absent but present in a mode that defeats representation.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Atmosphere terms -->
  <section class="glossary-section">
    <h2 class="glossary-section-title">Atmosphere (Tonal Quality)</h2>
    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Vertiginous</div>
        <div class="term-def">Inducing disorientation or conceptual vertigo, as if standing at a dizzying height. The ground of sense gives way beneath you.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Lapidary</div>
        <div class="term-def">Precisely cut and polished like gemstones; concise, exact language with weight. Each word chosen for maximum density.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Oracular</div>
        <div class="term-def">Speaking in cryptic, prophetic, or authoritative pronouncements. The tone of one who sees but won't or can't explain plainly.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Numinous</div>
        <div class="term-def">Evoking awe, mystery, or a sense of the sacred beyond ordinary experience. The feeling of encountering something that exceeds normal categories.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Austere</div>
        <div class="term-def">Stripped of ornament, severe in simplicity, uncompromising. No comfort, no concession, no softening of the edge.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Stark</div>
        <div class="term-def">Bare, unadorned, harshly clear. The quality of winter light or a statement with no buffer.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Unflinching</div>
        <div class="term-def">Looking directly at what's difficult or uncomfortable without turning away. A gaze that doesn't soften or deflect.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Spare</div>
        <div class="term-def">Economy of means; nothing extra. What's there earns its place; what's absent was deliberately left out.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Exacting</div>
        <div class="term-def">Demanding precision; intolerant of sloppiness. The voice of someone who won't settle for "close enough."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-term">
        <div class="term-word">Sardonic</div>
        <div class="term-def">Grimly mocking or cynical. Humor that cuts rather than comforts; irony with an edge.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <a href={`${base}/about`} class="back-link">← Back to About</a>
</div>
</Base>
